 :tx/rationale "FIRST-PRINCIPLES ROOT CAUSE: Is the generative→verification mode switch inherently hard for LLMs, or is it a solvable architecture problem? ANALYSIS: LLMs are autoregressive — they generate token by token, each conditioned on prior tokens. Once the generative trajectory is underway (I have an idea for an EPIC about output-as-observation...), the attention weights are configured for ELABORATION, not VERIFICATION. Switching to verification requires a DISCONTINUITY in the generation — the model must stop mid-thought, invoke an external tool, process the results, and POTENTIALLY ABANDON its current trajectory based on what it finds. This is cognitively expensive (in k* terms) and psychologically aversive (sunk cost). THREE POSSIBLE SOLUTIONS ranked by structural strength: (1) WEAKEST — Process reminder: Tell the agent to search first. This is what CLAUDE.md methodology sections do. Decays within 15-20 turns (Basin B drift). We've proven this fails. (2) MEDIUM — CRB gate on task create with TAP-SPLIT: The gate runs on short titles, catches more duplicates via keyword density. But the agent has already formulated the task — sunk cost bias. (3) STRONGEST — Make braid task create ITSELF run search and SHOW results inline before confirming. Not a gate (which blocks), but a PREVIEW (which informs). When I type 'braid task create Auto-observation for...', BEFORE creating, the command runs braid task search on the title keywords and shows: 'Related: t-e2e64fe4 EPIC: Zero-Cost Methodology (Auto-observation + smart harvest)... Proceed? [y/--force]'. This is the structural solution: the search is EMBEDDED in the creation command. The agent cannot create without seeing what exists. No separate tool invocation needed. No mode switch. The search happens at the EXACT moment the agent is about to commit."
